<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#D0BC90">Originally posted by ariana on 11-20-2002 01:45 AM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=20 COLS=75 WRAP="VIRTUAL">Krysanthl- I haven't finished yet, but so far I agree with your comments. I have found Divine Divinity a major favorable surprise. My luck with European-developed "CRPG" titles has been spotty at best and this publisher didn't have a track record in the genre that I knew about so I got the game a bit reluctantly and didn't take it out of the box until putting in a few hundred hours on Icewind Dale 2. I figured I would give it a day and if it was mediocre get on to the Neverwinter Nights Expansion, Avernum 2 or Homeworld (the latter two by Spiderweb Software - a small "shareware" house known for the high stability of its games and the loving detail that goes into them (making up for the dated graphics)).

Instead I am still plowing away at trying to finish "hardcore" (meaning without ever going back to a prior save except to recover from a crash or bug). The other games are sitting in THEIR boxes now.

If a "Divine Divinity 2" could be done the way Might and Magic 7 was done - using the existing engine with a few refinenements and thus able to get the game out in maybe 1/3 to 1/4 of the time a new engine would take - I would love to see it even if this did delay a new engine game by those 6 months or so. New engines take a long time. If they are going to use a new engine i don't care what the name is, and whether you can import characters from DD is irrelevent to me.

Alrik - your points are very well taken (not to mention accurate *grins* ) as to how little control many game developers have, these days. But there is still too much focus on "release now" and not enough on getting the game even 99% done and tested. The internet has hurt - making downloadable patches so ubiquitous. There are exception but they seem to be becoming more, er, exceptional *grins*. Sir-tech was definitely an exception but they are out of the business *sob* leaving Wizardry 8 as a testimonial to just how well a game can be done. New World Computing was another but Might and Magic 9 is a testimonial too - to how thoroughly they were raped after being bought by 3DO. The company doing Gothic 2 and Arx Fatalis is in financial trouble but is still holding up Gothic 2 (English version) to be sure to get it right - kudos to them (with apologies for forgetting the name - mental block - I hated Gothic).

------------------
Reality is for those who cannot cope with fantasy. Fortunately many of us do not have this problem.</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
